{"id":"1203.0245","submitter":"Jouko Mickelsson","authors":"Jouko Mickelsson","title":"The Chern Character of Certain Infinite Rank Bundles arising in Gauge\n  Theory","comments":"Talk delivered at the workshop \"Analysis, Geometry and Quantum Field\n  Theory\", in Potsdam, September 26-30, 2011, celebrating Steven Rosenberg's\n  60th birthday; Minor corrections; thanks to the careful referee!","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DG math-ph math.KT math.MP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A cocycle $\\Omega: P \\times G \\to H$ taking values in a Lie group $H$ for a\nfree right action of $G$ on $P$ defines a principal bundle $Q$ with the\nstructure group $H$ over $P/G.$ The Chern character of a vector bundle\nassociated to $Q$ defines then characteristic classes on $X.$ This observation\nbecomes useful in the case of infinite dimensional groups. It typically happens\nthat a representation of $G$ is not given by linear operators which differ from\nthe indentity by a trace-class operator. For this reason the Chern character of\na vector bundle associated to the principal fibration $P \\to P/G$ is\nill-defined. But it may happen that the Lie algebra representations of the\ngroup $H$ are given in terms of trace-class operators and therefore the Chern\ncharacter is well-defined; this observation is useful especially if the map\n$g\\mapsto \\Omega(p;g)$ is a homotopy equivalence on the image for any $p\\in P.$\nWe apply this method to the case $P= \\Cal A,$ the space of gauge connections in\na finite-dimensional vector bundle, and $G= \\Cal G$ is the group of (based)\ngauge transformations. The method for constructing the appropriate cocycle\n$\\Omega$ comes from ideas in quantum field theory, used to define the\nrenormalized gauge currents in a Fock space.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 Mar 2012 17:03:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 9 May 2012 07:36:28 GMT"}],"update_da